\begin_layout Subsection
Seasonal FFDI calculation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FFDI calculated with weather station data demonstrated to represent Victoria
 with more extreme bushfire weather compared to the results using reanalysis
 data.
 This difference is likely to occur for several reasons.
 FFDI variables from renalysis data do not correspond exactly to surface
 values.
 Reanalysis data is available from 1000 h-Pa level.
 The FFDI with weather station data is calcualted with values at 3 pm.
 Yet, reanalysis data for FFDI variables is available on a 6-hourly basis.
 This limited the availability of data to 4 pm values.
 There are intrinsic limitations in the reanalysis dataset already discussed
 in Chapter 2.
 Yet, simple linear scaling tecniques demonstrated to adjust the biases
 without signifincatly altering the correlations.
 The bias-correction of each variable will be examined in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most variables showed a significant correlation between weather station
 and 20CR data.
 Specifically, temperature, relative humidity and wind speed presented a
 similar variability with differences in magnitud.
 As already mentioned, linear scaling techniques were applied to correct
 the mean of these three variables.
 In this case the results were satisfactory since the correlations among
 weather stations and reanalysis data not significantly change—or even improve—.
 At the same time the bias-correction of reanalysis data produced similar
 outcomes in magnitude for the three variables.
 In contrast, the biases in precipiation could not be corrected using these
 tecniques.
 I decided then not to apply a bias-correction for this variable.
 I based this decision on the fact that the FFDI is less sensitive to changes
 to precipitation than the other three variables 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dowdy2009"

\end_inset

.
 A possible reason for this is that precipitation is not explicitly included
 in the FFDI equation, but rather part of the drought factor.
 This factor does not include precipitation explicitly either, since its
 computation requires the calculation of moisture deficits—in this research
 calculated with the KBDI—.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the bias-correction of temperature, relative humidity, and wind speed
 reanalysis data, the magnitude of FFDI results is very similar to the results
 using weather station data for the period 1974-2010.
 However, is important to notice that after the bias-corrrection process
 the reanalysis data over-estimates seasonal bushfire potential for both
 metrics of FFDI.
 For most years, this over-estimation is not large, with the exception of
 the years 1991 and 2001.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a final step, the FFDI computation was extended back in time to cover
 the period 1920-2010.
 The FFDI climate variables were bias-corrected for this period using the
 correction factors determined for the period 1974-2010.
 The calculation required to find the date—as further back in time as possible—w
ith the higher precipitation in order to set the soil moisture deficit to
 zero—factor in the KBDI calculation—.
 After the computation, a correlation analysis only for the period were
 FFDI with station data was availale—1974-2010—.
 The results were moderately correlated and similar to those obtained before
 extending the resutls.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results with FFDI
