\begin_layout Standard
The most notable feature in the relationship between variables in spring
 is the influence of the IOD.
 This climate mode of variability is strongly correlated with climate variables
 and bushfire weather.
 These results agree with the findings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 The authors found that positive IOD events drive hot and dry weather conditions
 in spring in Victoria.
 This effect reduces soil moisture and therefore dries fuel loads.
 The higher availability of these dry fuel loads makes the summer season
 more prone to bushfires.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The IOD exerts a stronger influence than ENSO in this season.
 This results also agrees with the findings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 However, is important to notice that I found a strong correlation of IOD
 with ENSO.
 Therefore, this result contributes the debate regarding the actual independence
 of IOD with respect to ENSO.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SAM does not have a significant influence in preconditioning bushfire seasons.
 This was an unexpected result, since the influence of SAM over rainfall
 in Victoria is well known 
